column1: #Text=Can you go and tell me your classifications ?
#Text=Yeah , we all ski in the standing class . LW6/8 -2
#Text=These guys are both LW2s because they 've both got on leg .
#Text=So we ski with just one leg , with crutches , whereas you 've got people who 've got below-knee amputations , they may have a longer stump and they ski with a prosthetic leg .
#Text=Toby and I have got to legally ski on one ski .
#Text=And what you were referring to before was the three classes of alpine skiing is standing , sitting , and blind .
#Text=So you 've all been to Paralympics before ?
#Text=Cam 's been to three , I 've been to two , and Mitch has been to one .
#Text=It 's also , obviously , skiing comes down to results .
#Text=I was there for experience , that was great .
#Text=My second one , I had bit of a disaster Paralympics .
#Text=The last one , I was able to come away with a couple of medals , so it was ...
#Text=Salt Lake City , was a little bit flatter .
#Text=Probably the type of hill ... it was still good , it was my first games , I enjoyed it .
#Text=Yeah , they usually prepare the courses reasonably well , ' cause they 've got a lot of course workers on the slopes .
#Text=That has a big influence on condition , not just the actual hill itself .

#Text=Vancouver was a challenge in the sense that we had terrible weather , terrible conditions and snow , even though it 's a good hill , whereas I think Sestriere we had sunshine virtually every day .
#Text=So a lot of it comes down to weather as well as the hill , the time of year .
#Text=In Australia , the big visibility Paralympics are the summer .

#Text=Do you guys ever feel vaguely — I know it 's the wrong question to ask — but do you ever feel vaguely cheated because you 're doing neglected , you do n't get the attention , the ABC ' s like " nah , we do n't want to cover you " ?
#Text=( laughter , interjections from elsewhere in the room )

#Text=Australia being a summer sport [ country ] , we 're aware that there 's going to be more focus on the summer games and particularly because there 's a larger ... there 's more athletes , there more events , there more medals .
#Text=There will always be more coverage for the summer games .
#Text=There 's no winter athlete that could walk away with more than five gold medals .
#Text=Whereas I think you can get a swimmer who might get eight gold medals .
#Text=So , it 's a different sort of exposure .

#Text=And realistically , it 's pretty unlikely for anybody in winter sport no matter how good they are , to walk away with more than one or two , just because of the nature of the sport , which is that anyone can crash .
#Text=You can be a great skier all the year and then crash .
#Text=[ uncertain ] can tell you about that in Vancouver .

#Text=The way that our sport moved after Salt Lake City is that instead of Cam and I skiing against each other , and only people with one leg , to being really competitive across those three classes , means that we think that the winter games are really , really competitive .
#Text=I think , if you took Michael Milton as an example , he won four gold at Salt Lake out of four events .
#Text=He won one silver in Torino out of four events with the new system , and he compared both events to be equal .
#Text=So , yeah , I think you 've got to look at the value of the medals at the winter games now has been quite high .
